article.description:
Shameka Christon and Cathrine Kraayeveld scored
22 points apiece, and Becky Hammon had 21 to lead the New York
Liberty to a 93-81 victory over the playoff-bound Washington
Mystics in the regular-season finale Sunday.
article.headline: Liberty end year well as playoff-bound Mystics chill
article.linkText: Liberty end year red-hot as playoff-bound Mystics chill
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Liberty closed their worst season
with their best stretch of the summer.

Shameka Christon and Cathrine Kraayeveld scored 22 points
apiece, and Becky Hammon had 21 to lead the Liberty to a 93-81
victory over the playoff-bound Washington Mystics on Sunday. New
York finished with seven wins in 10 games.

"We were just focusing on jumping out early," Kraayeveld said.
"That is something we need to continue to focus on next season.
We're just playing really well the past 10 games. We're proud of
the way we played."

Iciss Tillis added 10 points, and Christon also had a
season-high 10 rebounds for New York (11-23), which lost a
franchise-record 11 straight before its strong finish. The Liberty
also won consecutive games for just the fourth time this year and
matched their season-high scoring total.

"It took us a long time to get that chemistry," Kraayeveld
said. "This is what's going to happen in the future, the way we
played today, and we are excited about it."

Alana Beard scored 29 points, DeLisha Milton-Jones had 15, and
Nakia Sanford added 12 points and nine rebounds for the Mystics
(18-16).

"We'd like to go into the playoffs on a high note," Washington
coach Richie Adubato said. "We believe we had our high note Friday
against Detroit when we were down 29-11, came all the way back and
won the game. We understood that today was a game that we were
going to play a lot of people and we just didn't want to get
anybody hurt."

New York missed the playoffs for the third time in the WNBA's
10-year history, and finished with a losing record for just the
second season.

Tillis and Christon made two 3-pointers apiece in the final 8:03
to help the Liberty close the game with a 23-10 run after Beard
scored five straight points to give Washington a one-point lead

Christon's last 3 gave New York its biggest lead, 90-75 with
2:21 left.

Both teams shot 31-for-62 -- 50 percent -- from the field. The
Liberty were 13-for-26 on 3-pointers and 18-for-18 from the
free-throw line. The Mystics were 6 of 10 from 3-point range and
were 13 of 19 from the line.

"When you make shots, you win," Liberty coach Pat Coyle said.
"I've said it all year long. We had a lot of open looks.
Fortunately, today we knocked them down."

Washington, which won six of nine and finished 5-12 on the road,
will open the postseason at home against top-seeded Connecticut on
Friday night.

"Every game has some importance, but obviously this game did
not change anything as far as us making it into the playoffs,"
Beard said. "This team is in the right place now. We are really
jelling and coming together."

New York had a 13-0 run spanning halftime to take a 46-41 lead
on Hammon's layup with 8:52 remaining in the third quarter.

After Kraayeveld opened the game with a layup, Washington scored
11 straight points -- seven by Milton-Jones. The Liberty pulled to
14-13 on Christon's 3 with 3:36 left in the first quarter.

Nikki Blue's three-point play gave Washington its biggest lead
at 29-19 early in the second quarter. The Liberty scored seven
straight points to pull to 32-31 on Sherill Baker's steal and layup
with 5:37 to go in the first half.
